{"id":"2108.04505","submitter":"Dana Pizarro","authors":"Jos\\'e Correa (UCHILE), Dana Pizarro (TSE), Victor Verdugo (UOH)","title":"Optimal Revenue Guarantees for Pricing in Large Markets","comments":"Preparing full version","journal-ref":"SAGT, Sep 2021, Aarthus, Denmark","doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.OC","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Posted price mechanisms (PPM) constitute one of the predominant practices to\nprice goods in online marketplaces and their revenue guarantees have been a\ncentral object of study in the last decade. We consider a basic setting where\nthe buyers' valuations are independent and identically distributed and there is\na single unit on sale. It is well-known that this setting is equivalent to the\nso-called i.i.d. prophet inequality, for which optimal guarantees are known and\nevaluate to 0.745 in general (equivalent to a PPM with dynamic prices) and $1 -\n1/e \\approx 0.632$ in the fixed threshold case (equivalent to a fixed price\nPPM). In this paper we consider an additional assumption, namely, that the\nunderlying market is very large. This is modeled by first fixing a valuation\ndistribution F and then making the number of buyers grow large, rather than\nconsidering the worst distribution for each possible market size. In this\nsetting Kennedy and Kertz [Ann. Probab. 1991] breaks the 0.745 fraction\nachievable in general with a dynamic threshold policy. We prove that this large\nmarket benefit continue to hold when using fixed price PPMs, and show that the\nguarantee of 0.632 actually improves to 0.712. We then move to study the case\nof selling k identical units and we prove that the revenue gap of the fixed\nprice PPM approaches $1-1/\\sqrt{ 2k\\pi}$. As this bound is achievable without\nthe large market assumption, we obtain the somewhat surprising result that the\nlarge market advantage vanishes as $k$ grows.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 10 Aug 2021 08:18:20 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 20 Aug 2021 12:08:21 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-08-24"}
