{"id":"2108.04514","submitter":"Simon Malham","authors":"Simon J. A. Malham","title":"The non-commutative Korteweg--de Vries hierarchy and combinatorial Poppe\n  algebra","comments":"43 pages, 4 tables","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1016/j.physd.2022.133228","report-no":null,"categories":"nlin.SI math-ph math.AP math.CO math.MP","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  We give a constructive proof, to all orders, that each member of the\nnon-commutative potential Korteweg-de Vries hierarchy is a Fredholm\nGrassmannian flow and is therefore linearisable. Indeed we prove this for any\nlinear combination of fields from this hierarchy. That each member of the\nhierarchy is linearisable, and integrable in this sense, means that the time\nevolving solution can be generated from the solution to the corresponding\nlinear dispersion equation in the hierarchy, combined with solving an\nassociated linear Fredholm equation representing the Marchenko equation.\nFurther, we show that within the class of polynomial partial differential\nfields, at every order, each member of the non-commutative potential\nKorteweg--de Vries hierarchy is unique. Indeed, we prove to all orders, that\neach such member matches the non-commutative Lax hierarchy field, which is\ntherefore a polynomial partial differential field. We achieve this by\nconstructing the abstract combinatorial algebra that underlies the\nnon-commutative potential Korteweg-de Vries hierarchy. This algebra is the\nnon-commutative polynomial algebra over the real line generated by the set of\nall compositions endowed with the Poppe product. This product is the abstract\nrepresentation of the product rule for Hankel operators pioneered by Ch. Poppe\nfor integrable equations such as the Sine-Gordon and Korteweg-de Vries\nequations. Integrability of the hierarchy members translates, in the\ncombinatorial algebra, to proving the existence of a `Poppe polynomial'\nexpansion for basic compositions in terms of `linear signature expansions'.\nProving the existence of such Poppe polynomial expansions boils down to solving\na linear algebraic problem for the expansion coefficients, which we solve\nconstructively to all orders.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 10 Aug 2021 08:38:36 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-04-06"}
